'''Natalie Anne Coughlin Hall''' (born August 23, 1982) is an American competition swimmer and twelve-time Olympic medalist. While attending the [[University of California, Berkeley]], she became the first woman ever to swim the [[World record progression 100 metres backstroke#Long course 2|100-meter backstroke]] (long course) in less than one minute—ten days before her 20th birthday in 2002.  At the [[2008 Summer Olympics]], she became the first U.S. female athlete in modern Olympic history to win six medals in one Olympiad, and the first woman ever to win a 100-meter backstroke gold in two consecutive Olympics.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coughlin's 6 medals most by a US woman |url=http://stats.cbc.ca/olympics/story.asp?i=20080817063823933328708&%20ref=rec&tm=&src=OLYMPICS_DOLY_SWM |agency=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |publisher=(The Associated Press) |date=August 17, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110511093814/http://stats.cbc.ca/olympics/story.asp?i=20080817063823933328708&%20ref=rec&tm=&src=OLYMPICS_DOLY_SWM |archive-date=May 11, 2011 |url-status=dead |access-date=September 7, 2010}}</ref> At the [[2012 Summer Olympics]], she earned a bronze medal in the 4×100-meter freestyle relay.  

Coughlin's success has earned her the [[Swimming World Swimmers of the Year|World Swimmer of the Year Award]] once and [[Swimming World Swimmers of the Year#American Swimmer of the Year|American Swimmer of the Year Award]] three times.  She has won a total of sixty medals in major international competition, twenty-five gold, twenty-two silver, and thirteen bronze spanning the Olympics, the [[FINA World Aquatics Championships|World]], the [[Pan Pacific Swimming Championships|Pan Pacific]] Championships, and the [[Pan American Games]].

==Early years==
Coughlin was born in [[Vallejo, California]], the daughter of Jim and Zennie Coughlin.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.timesheraldonline.com/article/NH/20160813/SPORTS/160819919|title=Vallejo's Natalie Coughlin discusses her 12 Olympic medals, new role as analyst|access-date=2017-12-09|language=en}}</ref> She is of Irish and one quarter Filipino ancestry.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.asiancemagazine.com/2010/07/30/olympic-gold-medalist-natalie-coughlin |title=Olympic Silver Medalist Natalie Coughlin |access-date=July 5, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110807083425/http://www.asiancemagazine.com/2010/07/30/olympic-gold-medalist-natalie-coughlin |archive-date=August 7, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Coughlin first began swimming at Vallejo Aquatics Club when she was 8 years old, where she was coached by Tuffy Williams. <ref>Mel Orpilla, [http://www.orpilla.com/natalie.html "Natalie Coughlin: Olympic Hero"], ''orpilla.com'', publication_date. Retrieved 1-10-19.</ref>  She attended [[St. Catherine of Siena School (Vallejo, California)|St. Catherine of Siena School]] in Vallejo, for kindergarten through eighth grade, and then [[Carondelet High School]] in [[Concord, California]].  While in high school in 1998, she became the first swimmer to qualify for the Summer National in all fourteen events.<ref>[http://www.asianweek.com/2008/08/12/natalie-coughlin-wins-the-gold/ "Natalie Coughlin Wins the Gold!"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080916224026/http://www.asianweek.com/2008/08/12/natalie-coughlin-wins-the-gold/ |date=September 16, 2008 }}.  AsianWeek. Retrieved on August 20, 2008.</ref> Coughlin broke two individual national high school records in the 200-yard individual medley (1:58.45) and the 100-yard backstroke (52.86).  She graduated from Carondelet High School in 2000.

==College career==
Coughlin attended the [[University of California, Berkeley]], where she swam for coach [[Teri McKeever]]'s [[California Golden Bears]] swimming and diving team in [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) competition from 2001 to 2003.<ref name="Cal">{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041020082629/http://calbears.collegesports.com/sports/w-swim/mtt/coughlin_natalie00.html|archive-date=October 20, 2004|title=Natalie Coughlin|publisher=University of California, Berkeley|url=http://calbears.collegesports.com/sports/w-swim/mtt/coughlin_natalie00.html|date=2003|access-date=August 4, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>  During her three years as a Cal Bears swimmer, she won eleven individual NCAA national championships, and a twelfth NCAA relay title.  She was recognized as the NCAA Swimmer of the Year for three consecutive years, and she was a two-time recipient of the [[Honda Sports Award]] for Swimming and Diving, recognizing her as the outstanding college female swimmer in 2001–02 and 2002–03.<ref>Collegiate Women Sports Awards, [http://www.collegiatewomensportsawards.com/archives/swimdive  Past Honda Sports Award Winners for Swimming & Diving].  Retrieved December 1, 2014.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pac-12.com/article/2003/04/02/natalie-coughlin-wins-honda-award-swimming|title=Natalie Coughlin Wins Honda Award for Swimming|last=ConferenceApr 2|first=Pac-12|last2=2003|website=Pac-12|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>  ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' magazine named her its college Female Athlete of the Year.  Coughlin was inducted into the Cal Athletic Hall of Fame in 2014.<ref>"[http://www.calbears.com/ViewArticle.dbml?ATCLID=209511074  Cal Athletic Hall of Fame Adds 7 New Members]," CalBears.com (May 28, 2014).  Retrieved January 13, 2015.</ref> Coughlin graduated from Berkeley with a degree in psychology in the spring of 2005.<ref>{{citation|url=http://promise.berkeley.edu/spring_2008/balancing_act/|title=Balancing Act|work=The Promise of Berkeley|publisher=University of California, Berkeley|date=Spring 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.berkeley.edu/news/media/releases/2004/09/01_coughlin.shtml|title=Natalie Coughlin, five Olympic medals in hand, returns and learns to swim in the spotlight|date=September 1, 2004|author=Kahn, Jeffrey|access-date=August 4, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040902065721/http://www.berkeley.edu/news/media/releases/2004/09/01_coughlin.shtml|archive-date=September 2, 2004|url-status=live}}</ref>

==International career==

===2001–2003===
At the [[Swimming at the 2001 World Aquatics Championships|ninth World Aquatics Championships]] in Fukuoka, Japan, Coughlin won three medals—one gold, one silver, and one bronze.  She won her gold medal in the [[Swimming at the 2001 World Aquatics Championships – Women's 100 metre backstroke|100-meter backstroke]] with Diana Mocanu (Romania) taking the silver and Antje Buschschulte (Germany) taking the bronze.  Coughlin won her silver medal in the women's [[Swimming at the 2001 World Aquatics Championships – Women's 4 × 100 metre medley relay|4×100-meter medley relay]], teaming up with [[Megan Jendrick|Megan Quann]], [[Mary Descenza]], and [[Erin Phenix]]; the Australians won the gold (Calub, Jones, Thomas, Ryan).  Coughlin won her bronze medal in the [[Swimming at the 2001 World Aquatics Championships – Women's 50 metre backstroke|50-meter backstroke]]; fellow American Haley Cope won gold and Antje Buschschulte won the silver.

At the [[2002 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships|ninth Pan Pacific Championships]] in Yokohama, Japan, Coughlin won six medals—four golds and two silvers.  Coughlin won one of her gold medals in the women's [[2002 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – Women's 100 metre backstroke|100-meter backstroke]] with a time of 59.72, and another in the women's [[2002 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – Women's 100 metre butterfly|100-meter butterfly]] with a time of 57.88.  Coughlin won her third gold medal in the women's [[2002 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – Women's 100 metre freestyle|100-meter freestyle]] with a time of 53.99.  She won her fourth gold medal in the women's [[2002 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – Women's 4 × 200 metre freestyle relay|4×200-meter freestyle relay]] with Elizabeth Hill, Diana Munz, and Lindsay Benko.  She won her silver medals as a member of the second-place U.S. relay teams in the [[2002 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – Women's 4 × 100 metre freestyle relay|4×100-meter freestyle]] and [[2002 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – Women's 4 × 100 metre medley relay|4×100-meter medley]] events.

At the [[Swimming at the 2003 World Aquatics Championships|tenth World Aquatics Championships]] in Barcelona, Spain, Coughlin won two medals, including a gold and a silver. Coughlin won her gold medal in the women's [[Swimming at the 2003 World Aquatics Championships – Women's 4 × 100 metre freestyle relay|4×100-meter freestyle relay]] and a silver medal in the [[Swimming at the 2003 World Aquatics Championships – Women's 4 × 100 metre medley relay|4×100-medley relay]].

