Coughlin won the gold medal at the 2004 Olympics in the women's [[Swimming at the 2004 Summer Olympics – Women's 100 metre backstroke|100-meter backstroke]] event and won a silver medal as a member of the U.S. women's [[Swimming at the 2004 Summer Olympics – Women's 4 × 100 metre freestyle relay|4×100-meter freestyle relay]] team with [[Kara Lynn Joyce]], [[Amanda Weir]] and [[Jenny Thompson]].  She also broke a world record and won gold as a member of the [[Swimming at the 2004 Summer Olympics – Women's 4 × 200 metre freestyle relay|4×200-meter freestyle relay]], a silver in the [[Swimming at the 2004 Summer Olympics – Women's 4 × 100 metre medley relay|4×100-meter medley relay]], and a bronze in the [[Swimming at the 2004 Summer Olympics – Women's 100 metre freestyle|100-meter freestyle]].<ref>[http://www.nbcolympics.com/athletes/athlete=542/bio/ "Natalie Coughlin Profile & Bio"]. [[NBC Olympics]]. Retrieved on September 23, 2009.</ref><ref name="SR">{{cite Sports-Reference}}</ref>

===2005–2006===
At the [[Swimming at the 2005 World Aquatics Championships|eleventh World Aquatics Championships]] in Montreal, Quebec, Coughlin won five medals, including a gold and 2 silvers and 2 bronzes. Coughlin won a gold medal in the women's [[Swimming at the 2005 World Aquatics Championships – Women's 4 × 200 metre freestyle relay|200 m freestyle relay]] and silver medals in the [[Swimming at the 2003 World Aquatics Championships – Women's 4 × 100 metre medley relay|100 meter medley relay]] and the [[Swimming at the 2005 World Aquatics Championships – Women's 100 metre freestyle|100 m freestyle]]. She also won bronze medals in the [[Swimming at the 2005 World Aquatics Championships – Women's 100 metre backstroke|100 m backstroke]] and the [[Swimming at the 2005 World Aquatics Championships – Women's 4 × 100 metre freestyle relay|100m freestyle relay]].

Coughlin worked as an in-studio host for [[MSNBC]] during the [[2006 Winter Olympics]] in Turin, Italy.{{cn|date=July 2019}}

===2007 World Aquatics Championships===
{{see also|Swimming at the 2007 World Aquatics Championships}}

At the [[2007 World Aquatics Championships]], Coughlin won five medals: two gold, two silver, and one bronze.  In her first event, the [[Swimming at the 2007 World Aquatics Championships – Women's 4 × 100 metre freestyle relay|4×100-meter freestyle relay]], Coughlin won a silver medal along with [[Lacey Nymeyer]], [[Amanda Weir]], and [[Kara Lynn Joyce]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/swimming/racearchives/2007/melbourne2007/F73_ResByHeat_107_Finals_Women_4x100_Free.pdf |title=12th FINA World Championships: 4×100 m freestyle relay final |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=September 7, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120120123120/http://www.omegatiming.com/swimming/racearchives/2007/melbourne2007/F73_ResByHeat_107_Finals_Women_4x100_Free.pdf |archive-date=January 20, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The following day, in the [[Swimming at the 2007 World Aquatics Championships – Women's 100 metre butterfly|100-meter butterfly]], she placed third in the final with a time of 57.34, an American record.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/swimming/racearchives/2007/melbourne2007/F73_ResByHeat_101_Finals_Women_100_Fly.pdf |title=12th FINA World Championships: 100 m butterfly final |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=September 7, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091004014415/http://www.omegatiming.com/swimming/racearchives/2007/melbourne2007/F73_ResByHeat_101_Finals_Women_100_Fly.pdf |archive-date=October 4, 2009 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In the [[Swimming at the 2007 World Aquatics Championships – Women's 100 metre breaststroke|100-meter backstroke]] final, held the following day, she broke her own world record set in 2002 with a time of 59.44.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/swimming/racearchives/2007/melbourne2007/F73_ResByHeat_109_Finals_Women_100_Back.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070407113814/http://www.omegatiming.com/swimming/racearchives/2007/melbourne2007/F73_ResByHeat_109_Finals_Women_100_Back.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=April 7, 2007 |title=12th FINA World Championships: 100 m backstroke final |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=September 7, 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |title=World Championships: Keeping the String Going, Natalie Coughlin Breaks World Record in 100 Backstroke |url=http://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/lane9/news/14345.asp |magazine=Swimming World Magazine |date=March 27, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120825214628/http://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/lane9/news/14345.asp |archive-date=August 25, 2012 |access-date=September 7, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> After a day of rest, Coughlin was back in the pool to swim the lead-off leg in the [[Swimming at the 2007 World Aquatics Championships – Women's 4 × 200 metre freestyle relay|4×200-meter freestyle relay]].  Swimming in lane eight, Coughlin set the American record with a time of 1:56.43, to break [[Katie Hoff]]'s one-day-old record of 1:57.09.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=World Championships: United States Takes Down World Record in 800 Free Relay; Natalie Coughlin Sets American Record in 200 Freestyle |url=http://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/lane9/news/14403.asp |magazine=Swimming World Magazine |date=March 29, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120825214634/http://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/lane9/news/14403.asp |archive-date=August 25, 2012 |access-date=September 7, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> [[Dana Vollmer]], Lacey Nymeyer, and Katie Hoff each extended the lead and the final time of 7:50.09 was a world record.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/swimming/racearchives/2007/melbourne2007/F73_ResByHeat_126_Finals_Women_4x200_Free.pdf |title=12th FINA World Championships: 4×200 m freestyle relay final |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=September 7, 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091004013906/http://www.omegatiming.com/swimming/racearchives/2007/melbourne2007/F73_ResByHeat_126_Finals_Women_4x200_Free.pdf |archive-date=October 4, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The following day, Coughlin finished in 4th place in the [[Swimming at the 2007 World Aquatics Championships – Women's 100 metre freestyle|100-meter freestyle]] despite setting the championship record in the semi-finals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/swimming/racearchives/2007/melbourne2007/F73_ResByHeat_122_Finals_Women_100_Free.pdf |title=12th FINA World Championships: 100 m freestyle final |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=September 7, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070406023102/http://www.omegatiming.com/swimming/racearchives/2007/melbourne2007/F73_ResByHeat_122_Finals_Women_100_Free.pdf |archive-date=April 6, 2007 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In her last event, the [[Swimming at the 2007 World Aquatics Championships – Women's 4 × 100 metre medley relay|4×100-meter medley relay]], Coughlin won a silver medal along with [[Tara Kirk]], [[Rachel Komisarz]], and Lacey Nymeyer.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/swimming/racearchives/2007/melbourne2007/F73_ResByHeat_137_Finals_Women_4x100_Medley.pdf |title=12th FINA World Championships: 4×100 m medley relay final |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=September 7, 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070405213524/http://www.omegatiming.com/swimming/racearchives/2007/melbourne2007/F73_ResByHeat_137_Finals_Women_4x100_Medley.pdf |archive-date=April 5, 2007 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>

===2008 Beijing Summer Olympics===
{{see also|Swimming at the 2008 Summer Olympics}}

{{MedalTableTop |name=no |header=[[Swimming at the 2008 Summer Olympics|2008 Olympics]] |medals=
