In Coughlin's second Olympics appearance, at Beijing in 2008, she became the first American female athlete to win six medals in one Olympics.<ref name="Aron2008_08_18">"The six medals she won are the most by an American woman in any sport, breaking the record she tied four years ago. Her career total matches the third-most by any U.S. athlete." {{cite news |url=http://stats.cbc.ca/olympics/story.asp?i=20080817063823933328708&%20ref=rec&tm=&src=OLYMPICS_DOLY_SWM |title=Coughlin's 6 medals most by a US woman |author=Jaime Aron |date=August 17, 2008 |publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110511093814/http://stats.cbc.ca/olympics/story.asp?i=20080817063823933328708&%20ref=rec&tm=&src=OLYMPICS_DOLY_SWM |archive-date=May 11, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> She was elected joint captain of the US women's swimming team together with five-time Olympian [[Dara Torres]] and four-time Olympian [[Amanda Beard]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/olympics_blog/2008/07/us-swim-teams-n.html |title=U.S. swim teams name captains for Beijing |work=Los Angeles Times |date=July 30, 2008 |access-date=May 19, 2010}}</ref> Coughlin won the gold medal in the [[Swimming at the 2008 Summer Olympics – Women's 100 metre backstroke|100-meter backstroke]] at those Olympiads, the inaugural woman to successfully defend a gold medal standing in that event. her world records was surpassed in the semi final by [[Kirsty Coventry]], would take the silver. Standing on the medal platform, her lip was still bleeding having bitten it during the race to distract her from the pain in her legs.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/olympics/2008/08/why_the_water_cube_is_so_fast.html |title=Why The Water Cube Is So Fast |access-date=August 12, 2008}}</ref> She won a silver medal in the [[Swimming at the 2008 Summer Olympics – Women's 4 × 100 metre freestyle relay|4×100-meter freestyle relay]], swimming with [[Lacey Nymeyer]], Kara Lynn Joyce and Dara Torres, and also won bronze medals in the [[Swimming at the 2008 Summer Olympics – Women's 200 metre individual medley|200-meter individual medley]], [[Swimming at the 2008 Summer Olympics – Women's 4 × 200 metre freestyle relay|4×200-meter freestyle relay]], and the [[Swimming at the 2008 Summer Olympics – Women's 100 metre freestyle|100-meter freestyle]].  She won a silver medal in her final race in the [[Swimming at the 2008 Summer Olympics – Women's 4 × 100 metre medley relay|4×100-meter medley relay]] swimming with [[Rebecca Soni]], [[Christine Magnuson]], and Dara Torres.

===2010 US Summer Nationals and Pan Pacific Championships===

After taking an 18-month hiatus from swimming, Coughlin returned to competition at the [[2010 USA Swimming Championships|2010 Conoco Phillips Summer Nationals]]. Coughlin qualified for Pan Pacific in the 100-meter backstroke with a time of 1:00.14.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.star-meets.org/results/Nats/2010/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=August 9, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100807195721/http://www.star-meets.org/results/Nats/2010/ |archive-date=August 7, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>

Before racing at the [[2010 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships|Pan Pacs]], Coughlin, along with [[Amanda Beard]], was elected co-captain of Team USA once again.  In the finals of the [[2010 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – Women's 100 metre freestyle|100-meter freestyle]], Natalie Coughlin won the gold, making a new [[List of Pan Pacific Championships records in swimming|Pan Pacific record]] (53.67).  In the finals of the [[2010 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – Women's 100 metre backstroke|100-meter backstroke]], Coughlin finished third (59.70) behind Australia's [[Emily Seebohm]] and Japan's [[Aya Terakawa]].  Coughlin won two more golds when starting off both the [[2010 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – Women's 4 × 100 metre freestyle relay|4×100-meter freestyle relay]] and the [[2010 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships – Women's 4 × 100 metre medley relay|4×100-meter medley relay]].<ref>http://www.star-meets.org/results/PanPacs/2010/</ref>

===2011 World Aquatics Championships===

At the [[Swimming at the 2011 World Aquatics Championships|14th World Aquatics Championships]] in Shanghai, China, Coughlin won three medals–one gold, one silver, and one bronze.  She won a gold medal in the women's [[Swimming at the 2011 World Aquatics Championships – Women's 4 × 100 metre medley relay|4×100-meter medley relay]] with fellow Americans Rebecca Soni, Dana Vollmer, and Missy Franklin with a time of 3:52.36.  She won a silver medal in the women's [[Swimming at the 2011 World Aquatics Championships – Women's 4 × 100 metre freestyle relay|4×100-meter freestyle relay]] with fellow Americans Missy Franklin, Jessica Hardy, and Dana Vollmer with a time of 3:34.47 with the Netherlands touching first with a time of 3:33.96.  She won a bronze medal in the women's [[Swimming at the 2011 World Aquatics Championships – Women's 100 metre backstroke|100-meter backstroke]], her only individual medal at these championships, with a 59.15.  Coughlin led for the entire race, when in the last couple meters, Zhao Jing and Anastasia Zueva edged her out.

===2012 London Summer Olympics===
{{See also|Swimming at the 2012 Summer Olympics}}

At the [[2012 United States Olympic Trials (swimming)|2012 United States Olympic Trials]] in Omaha, Nebraska, the U.S. qualifying event for the Olympics, the 29-year-old veteran Coughlin found herself in competition with a younger generation of American swimmers.  In order to qualify for the U.S team in a given individual event, swimmers are required to finish among the top two.  In the finals of the 100-meter backstroke, she finished third behind teenagers [[Missy Franklin]] and [[Rachel Bootsma]], and finished seventh in the 100-meter butterfly.  Coughlin also competed in the 100-meter freestyle, and finished sixth, qualifying to compete as a member of the U.S. women's team in the preliminaries of the 4×100-meter freestyle relay.

At the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] in London, she swam in the qualifying round of the [[Swimming at the 2012 Summer Olympics – Women's 4 × 100 metre freestyle relay|4×100-meter freestyle relay]], and did not swim in the 4×100-meter final, but earned a bronze medal when the U.S. team placed third in the final.  It was her twelfth Olympic medal, tying the record previously set by American swimmers [[Jenny Thompson]] and [[Dara Torres]] for the most career Olympic medals won by a female U.S. athlete.<ref>{{cite news |title=Left off finals team, Coughlin still earns 12th medal |url=http://www.sfgate.com/sports/article/Natalie-Coughlin-garners-12th-medal-3743939.php |access-date=July 28, 2012 |newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle |date=July 28, 2012 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref>

===2013 World Aquatics Championships===
At the 2013 Phillips 66 National Championships, which also served as the selection meet for the World Championships, Coughlin decided to only take up the sprint freestyles and swam the 50 and 100-meter freestyle events. Coughlin qualified for the 50-meter freestyle and the 4×100-meter freestyle relay. Coughlin finished first in the 50-meter freestyle with a 24.97, just ahead of 16-year-old [[Simone Manuel]], who swam a 25.01.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010D020001001402FFFFFFFFFFFF02 |title=2013 Phillips 66 National Championships Women's 50m Freestyle Results |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=July 6, 2013}}</ref> With the first-place finish in the 50-meter freestyle, Coughlin ensured herself a relay spot since she had finished 5th in the 100-meter freestyle, with a time of 54.04.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=00010D020001001502FFFFFFFFFFFF02 |title=2013 Phillips 66 National Championships Women's 100m Freestyle Results |publisher=Omega Timing |access-date=July 6, 2013}}</ref>

She won a gold medal at the event on the first night of swimming competition in the [[Swimming at the 2013 World Aquatics Championships – Women's 4 × 100 metre freestyle relay|4×100 freestyle relay]]. She went second for team USA and swam her leg in 52.98 seconds; she was one of only 6 women in the field of 32 to break the 53-second barrier.

In her final triumph, two months before her 33rd birthday in 2015, she set an American women's record of 27.51 seconds in the 50-meter backstroke.

==Post-swimming career and media appearances==
Coughlin was the spokeswoman for C20 Coconut Water.<ref>http://www.bevnet.com/news/2011/c2o-pure-coconut-water-recruits-11-time-medalist-swimmer-natalie-coughlin</ref>

One of Coughlin's favorite hobbies is cooking. During the [[2008 Summer Olympics]], she was invited to prepare a Chinese-themed dish on ''[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today]]''. She has appeared as a judge on ''[[Iron Chef America]]''.<ref>Crooks, Peter. [http://www.diablomag.com/Diablo-Magazine/November-2008/Gold-Medal-Gourmet/ " Gold Medal Gourmet"] Diablo Magazine, Nov 2008.</ref> She appeared on [[Food Network]]'s ''[[Chopped (TV series)|Chopped]]'' Sport Stars episode that first aired on September 3, 2013.

Coughlin competed in [[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. season 9)|season 9]] of ''[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. TV series)|Dancing with the Stars]]'' with [[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. season 1)|season 1]] professional champion, [[Alec Mazo]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pophangover.com/?p=4341 |title=Dancing with the Stars Season 9 Cast |access-date=August 17, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090819004443/http://pophangover.com/?p=4341 |archive-date=August 19, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Joyce Eng |title=''Dancing with the Stars'' 2009 Season 9 Cast Revealed! |url=http://www.tvguide.com/Dancing-Stars/Dancing-Stars-2009-1009007.aspx |work=TVGuide.com |date=August 17, 2009 |access-date=August 17, 2009}}</ref> She was eliminated on the fifth episode.

Coughlin appeared in the 2012 ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' [[Sports Illustrated Swimsuit Issue|Swimsuit Issue]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2012_swimsuit/painting/natalie-coughlin/12_natalie-coughlin_1.html |work=CNN |title=Natalie Coughlin – Body Paint – 2012 Sports Illustrated Swimsuit Edition – SI.com |access-date=February 17, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120216225542/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2012_swimsuit/painting/natalie-coughlin/12_natalie-coughlin_1.html |archive-date=February 16, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> She has also written a book called ''Golden Girl''.

In 2013, Coughlin appeared in ''[[Chopped (TV series)|Chopped]]'' where she lost in the final round to [[Danica Patrick]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://swimswam.com/natalie-coughlin-falls-danica-patrick-chopped-sports-stars-final |work=swimswam.com |title=Natalie Coughlin Falls to Danica Patrick in "Chopped" Sports Stars Final |date=September 3, 2013 |access-date=June 8, 2016}}</ref> While on the show she mentioned she grows a vegetable and herb garden in her backyard, as well as raising backyard chickens.

Coughlin appeared on one of the covers for the 2015 ''[[ESPN The Magazine]]'' ''[[The Body Issue]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/olympics/story/_/page/bodynataliecoughlin/olympic-swimmer-natalie-coughlin-shares-secrets-12-medals-espn-magazine-body-issue |title=Olympic swimmer Natalie Coughlin shares the secrets to her 12 medals – ESPN The Magazine Body Issue}}</ref> and in July/August 2016, the cover of [[Self (magazine)]]'s Olympics themed issue.

Also in 2015, Coughlin became a brand ambassador and investor in a frozen food company, [[Luvo Inc.]]<ref>'Inc.com (Posted August 10, 2015) [http://www.inc.com/zoe-henry/why-derek-jeter-russell-wilson-olympic-swimmer-invested-in-luvo.html "Why Derek Jeter, Russell Wilson, and a 12-Time Olympic Medalist Invested in This Food Startup"]. Retrieved August 10, 2015</ref>

==Personal life==
In April 2009, Coughlin married Ethan Hall, the Crow Canyon Sharks swim coach.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theswimaids.com/2009/04/29/did-paps-crash-natalie-coughlins-wedding/ |title=Did Paps Crash Natalie Coughlin's Wedding? |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090716002330/http://www.theswimaids.com/2009/04/29/did-paps-crash-natalie-coughlins-wedding/ |archive-date=July 16, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The couple welcomed a daughter on October 17, 2018.<ref>{{cite news |title=Olympic Gold Medalist Natalie Coughlin Gives Birth To Baby Girl |url=https://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/news/olympic-gold-medalist-natalie-coughlin-gives-birth-to-baby-girl/ |access-date=7 July 2019 |publisher=Swimming World Magazine |date=October 18, 2018}}</ref> Coughlin announced May 27, 2020 via Instagram she is expecting a second child in a few months.  On October 27, 2020 she posted a picture on Instagram of her newborn son Ozzie.

